# 00 — BDO Architecture

**Status:** Draft v1.0

---

# Overview

Bitcoin Digital Objects (BDOs) are built as an open architecture composed of independent layers.

Each layer has a single responsibility.

Each higher layer depends on the layers below it without replacing them.

This separation allows the ecosystem to evolve while preserving interoperability.

---

# Architecture

```
                Applications
        (wallets, games, marketplaces,
         communities, ticketing, etc.)
                       ▲
                       │
                 Experiences
                       ▲
                       │
                Capabilities
                       ▲
                       │
                Verification
                       ▲
                       │
                  Ownership
                       ▲
                       │
                   Identity
                       ▲
                       │
         Bitcoin Digital Objects
                       ▲
                       │
                  STAS-01
      (Open Interoperability Specification)
                       ▲
                       │
               Taproot Assets
                       ▲
                       │
                   Bitcoin
```

---

# Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Responsibility |
|--------|----------------|
| Bitcoin | Security, consensus and final settlement |
| Taproot Assets | Bitcoin-native digital asset primitives |
| STAS-01 | Open interoperability specification |
| Bitcoin Digital Objects | Open ownership category |
| Identity | Defines what an object is |
| Ownership | Defines who controls the object |
| Verification | Allows independent validation |
| Capabilities | Describe what applications may do with the object |
| Experiences | User-facing interactions built by applications |
| Applications | Wallets, games, communities, marketplaces and services |

---

# Conceptual Flow

The architecture follows a simple progression.

Bitcoin provides security.

Taproot Assets provide Bitcoin-native digital asset primitives.

STAS-01 defines how compatible implementations exchange and interpret those assets.

Bitcoin Digital Objects establish a shared conceptual ownership category.

Identity gives every object continuity.

Ownership assigns control.

Verification replaces trust.

Capabilities describe possible interactions.

Applications transform those capabilities into user experiences.

---

# Separation of Responsibilities

Each layer intentionally solves a different problem.

Bitcoin does not define digital ownership semantics.

Taproot Assets do not define interoperability.

STAS-01 does not define applications.

Bitcoin Digital Objects do not define user interfaces.

Applications do not define ownership.

Keeping responsibilities separated allows every layer to evolve independently.

---

# Open Ecosystem

The BDO architecture is intentionally open.

Multiple specifications may represent Bitcoin Digital Objects.

Multiple implementations may support those specifications.

Multiple applications may interpret the same object.

Interoperability emerges through shared standards rather than centralized platforms.

---

# Design Philosophy

The architecture follows a few fundamental principles.

- Build on Bitcoin.
- Keep standards open.
- Separate concepts from implementations.
- Separate ownership from experiences.
- Replace trust with verification.
- Maximize interoperability.
- Allow applications to innovate freely.

---

# Relationship Between Repositories

The Bitcoin Digital Objects ecosystem is intentionally divided into independent repositories.

```
bitcoin-digital-objects
        │
        ├── Defines the conceptual architecture
        │
        ▼
stas-standard
        │
        ├── Defines the interoperability specification
        │
        ▼
Reference Implementations
        │
        ├── Supermultiverse
        ├── BTCPay Plugin
        └── Future compatible implementations
```

Each repository has a different purpose.

This repository defines concepts.

STAS-01 defines technical interoperability.

Reference implementations demonstrate how the architecture can be applied.

---

# Guiding Principle

> Bitcoin secures ownership.

> Open standards enable interoperability.

> Applications create experiences.